<div id="subtree-container" class="subtree-container"><div class="aea2d7dde423afa7ad9351a0886150a8-scss b51b00c1669ad99a1c607cd1e77c2824-scss" style="inset: 346px 269px 0px 0px; justify-content: flex-end;"><div class="afeebf1df237d4103108ba40799802d6-scss"><div class="c13443431e58facf06f9d12490b92a82-scss" style="width: 90vw; max-width: 8.5in;"><div class="_0df5ec6b9902d7d22ccfa3ebb4f35211-scss">On-site Construction</div><div class="e5e059a27f4c194020f0d961a3cb5989-scss" dir="auto"><div class="fr-view"><p id="isPasted">For on-site constructed solutions, the guidelines are as follows.&nbsp;</p>
<p>Regardless of the method, when quantifying these elements and their associated finishes using models, it's crucial to consider the net square area (m² or ft²) as the quantification unit, considering that all voids are already accounted for in the model.&nbsp;</p>
<p>During the early estimates, one of either of these methods can be performed:</p>
<ol>
<li>Use the <strong>Room information to derive the quantities</strong> of the walls, floor, ceilings, and their finishes</li>
<li>Develop a <strong>model using multi-layered objects</strong> and applying average prices to the element composition</li>
</ol>
<p style="text-align: left;">For more accurate and detailed quantities of on-site constructed elements, especially during more advanced project stages, it's essential to model walls, floors, ceilings, and their finishes as distinct single-layered objects, as demonstrated in Figure 08.&nbsp;</p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><br></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><img src="https://private.lodplanner.com/projects/11696/plan-content/1700585348802_96ca236e-620e-4fca-a3ef-a4e55d6f3da1.png?Expires=1768815902&amp;Signature=oJImmwIMds6qKU2tYdPrQbWDITjYrKnhlZPtDhJbvP3W0pK25obCvCfh7goYm6pMiKhXnve2uMLO~UbcLDWhihYOEzekjuMv2dLfokFcej2AiNeklJ8B99ivLdvVm1hMhITKQRIl7pn6t2QylKtKzTBiTAXjZjOiRjLkfV6AqV~PvK6wcWpHCErQedgl1zEook-crYHkryC0HIlgGBZ8kUy-xO0DxLRGIPCScoK7tXQ0PTEGLnplHdzNCv2H-qwMVegok~ZdtoxyS3JasIy~3dM0~HvbsX19nYDuEAlx2LdhsCy9n5MpU5elf9zgx0snMG7i8l9aaXlYX5TcJSW~Sw__&amp;Key-Pair-Id=APKAJRIVA6WNZT4BZJPQ" class="fr-fic fr-dii" style="width: 852px;"></p>
<p><br></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><em>Figure 08 – Example of walls modelled as single separate-layered objects.</em></p>
<p><br></p>
<p>In this approach, each material should be represented by a separate model element, differentiating the core construction element from the finishes that may be applied to it.&nbsp;</p>
<p>However, for composite construction elements that typically have a standardized composition, such as a drywall steel frame with gypsum plasterboards, modeling them as layered elements is feasible.&nbsp;</p>
<p>Two instances of this can be observed in Figure 09 and described below.&nbsp;</p>
<ul>
<li>
<strong>Example A:</strong> Illustrates a masonry wall element (comprising three layers: mortar + masonry + mortar) with a tiling finish element (single layer). In this scenario, the tiling finish <strong>extends 10cm above the ceiling</strong>.</li>
<li>
<strong>Example B:</strong> Illustrates a drywall element (consisting of three layers: gypsum board + steel frame + gypsum board) with a paint finish element (single layer). The paint finish <strong>extends to the ceiling</strong>.</li>
</ul>
<p><br></p>
<div style="text-align: center;"><img src="https://private.lodplanner.com/projects/11696/plan-content/1700585385889_5491d48a-4c4d-48fa-b40a-4d0ae15cc438.png?Expires=1768815902&amp;Signature=QRakmUJCaFcjpXUZMqg3xmx47Q7rhYXFYLyhbQV-kfFFTTbCsjaeFS1GBZRNU8xD-Ac5SRZ1oqkstUdJFc8glbodfNk3q3rxxB7JyIGVJQPXgmeUqOVK7xdlxN16WUPqe99WiwGXZC8QArpVby-z-0cwWWyezRB22yolpEIw8UV6Gnvown2Mt2qIDONqlSsAYbtfpehUIDvs9g2xWFdWgZNVoa1RZhGtSWnhqq-5uzxDHaOqx5LgMbEmQ15DCzKWWMz3qPIWoXpVQF3q84SvI3dV1Mu-sL2OIuyAjUUB09ukDclIal9mQtdeN-GFsF9jFVIwCMWy1jGoPoBz4-BVkA__&amp;Key-Pair-Id=APKAJRIVA6WNZT4BZJPQ" class="fr-fic fr-dii" style="width: 885px;"></div>
<p><br></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><em>Figure 09 - Examples of single separate-layered walls, considering the height according to each constructive need of each material.&nbsp;</em></p>
<p style="text-align: left;"><br></p>
<p style="text-align: left;" id="isPasted">This separation method allows better control over the modeling considerations specific to each material, resulting in more accurate quantities.</p></div></div></div></div></div></div>